03925nam a22006255i 9780292799745DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211995txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927997457 a10.7560/7555672doi  a(DE-B1597)587154  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aF395.M5N39 1995 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a323.3/52/089687207641 aNavarro, Armando, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMexican American Youth Organization :bAvant-Garde of the Chicano Movement in Texas /cArmando Navarro. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©1995  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tPhotographs -- tIntroduction. Paradigm for the Etiology of the Chicano Movement -- t1 The Chicano Movement: Impact of Endogenous Antagonisms -- t2 The Chicano Youth Movement: Catalyst for Change -- t3 MAYO: A Cadre Organization of Organizers -- t4 MAYO: Protagonist for Educational Change -- t5 MAYO: Advocate for Social Change -- t6 MAYO: Precursor to the Raza Unida Party -- t7 MAYO: Decline and Demise -- tEpilogue -- tAppendixes -- t1. "El Plan Espiritual de Aztlan" -- t2. MAYO Membership Requirements -- t3. Crystal City School Walkout Demands -- t4. "El Plan de Del Rio" -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmong the protest movements of the 1960s, the Mexican American Youth Organization (MAYO) emerged as one of the principal Chicano organizations seeking social change. By the time MAYO evolved into the Raza Unida Party (RUP) in 1972, its influence had spread far beyond its Crystal City, Texas, origins. Its members precipitated some thirty-nine school walkouts, demonstrated against the Vietnam War, and confronted church and governmental bodies on numerous occasions. Armando Navarro here offers the first comprehensive assessment of MAYO's history, politics, leadership, ideology, strategies and tactics, and activist program. Interviews with many MAYO and RUP organizers and members, as well as first-hand knowledge drawn from his own participation in meetings, presentations, and rallies, enrich the text. This wealth of material yields the first reliable history of this extremely vocal and visible catalyst of the Chicano Movement. The book will add significantly to our understanding of Sixties protest movements and the social and political conditions that gave them birth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aCompean, Mario C.1 aCompean, Mario C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/75556740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292799745423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292799745/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK